ule of conditioning of the Bayesian theory: set functions that need only be what Choquet called "monotone of order of infinity." and Dempster's rule for combining such set functions. This rule, together with the idea of "weights of evidence," leads to both an extensive new theory and a better understanding of the Bayesian theory. The book concludes with a brief treatment of statistical inference and a discussion of the limitations of epistemic probability. Appendices contain mathematical proofs, which are relatively elementary and seldom depend on mathematics more advanced that the binomial theorem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEvidence. 0aMathematical statistics. 0aProbabilities. 7aMATHEMATICS / History & Philosophy.2bisacsh  aBayesian belief functions.  aGranger, Thomas.  aHacking, Ian.  aJeffrey, Richard.  aKeynes, John Maynard.  aassessment of evidence.  achance density.  aconfidence sets.  adecision theory.  adegree of belief.  adissonance.  aepistemology.  aexponential function.  ajudgment and evidence.  alikelihood.  alinear models.  aorthogonal sum.  aplausibility.  aproposition.  aquasi support function.  ascientific hypotheses.  astatistical estimation.  atest statistic.  aupper probability.1 aDempster, A. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShafer, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691214696zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691214696423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691214696.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-199